<p>Say that I havea following template:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;!-- Here can be other tags, js variable, which are the same for all controllers --&gt; &lt;div class="common-part"&gt;SomeContent&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;!-- Here is the specific part for each controller --&gt;     &lt;div class="specific-part"&gt;     &lt;a&gt;{{someText}}&lt;/a&gt; &lt;!-- for controller 1--&gt;     &lt;input ng-click="someAction()" ng-model="someText"/&gt; &lt;!-- for controller 2--&gt;     &lt;p ng-click="someAction()"&gt;{{someText}}&lt;/p&gt; &lt;!-- for controller 2--&gt; &lt;/div&gt; </code></pre>  <p>So template generally is the same, but different controller "have to put" own element. Pay your abstention, that tag for controller may have <code>ng-click</code> attribute or not.</p>  <p>I have 2 basic approaches to resolve this situation:</p>  <ol> <li>Each controller <code>put</code> into type into <code>$scope.tagType</code>. View template "looks" at this variable and render approriate piece of html.</li> <li>A veiw call <code>$scope.getTag</code> where controller store tag reprensentation.</li> </ol>  <p>What is more approriate? Are there other methodics/aproaches for that?</p>